  1. Install two packages gganimate and gifski then restart Rstudio. Using the Adult Census Income data, make an animation using geom_point and transition_states.

  2. Using the Adult Census Income data, make an animation using geom_bar and transition_states.

    library(ggplot2)
    ## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.4.3
    library(gganimate)
    ## Warning: package 'gganimate' was built under R version 4.4.3
    library(gifski)
    ## Warning: package 'gifski' was built under R version 4.4.3
    library(readr)
    ## Warning: package 'readr' was built under R version 4.4.3
    library(dplyr)

df <- read_csv("C:/Users/student/Downloads/adult_census.csv")

df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = hours.per.week, color = income)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  transition_states(education,
                    transition_length = 2,
                    state_length = 1) +
  labs(title = "Education level: {closest_state}")

  3. Use the WHOs dataset at this link. Make a top-10 bar race by months between countries on the number of deaths by Covid 19 in 2021.

    df <- read_csv("C:/Users/student/Downloads/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv")   
names(df)
    ## [1] "Date_reported"     "Country_code"      "Country"          
## [4] "WHO_region"        "New_cases"         "Cumulative_cases" 
## [7] "New_deaths"        "Cumulative_deaths"
    library(dplyr)
library(readr)
library(lubridate)
    ## Warning: package 'lubridate' was built under R version 4.4.3
    top10_monthly <- df %>%
  mutate(
    Date_reported = as.Date(Date_reported),
    year = year(Date_reported),
    month_date = floor_date(Date_reported, unit = "month"),
    month_label = format(month_date, "%b %Y")
  ) %>%
  filter(year == 2021) %>%
  group_by(month_label, Country) %>%
  summarise(month_deaths = sum(New_deaths, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(month_label) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = month_deaths, n = 10, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  arrange(month_label, month_deaths) %>%
  mutate(rank = row_number()) %>%
  ungroup()
    p <- ggplot(top10_monthly,
            aes(x = month_deaths,
                y = reorder(Country, rank),
                fill = Country)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    x = "Number of deaths in month",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Top-10 countries by Covid-19 deaths\n{closest_state}"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "none",
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold")
  ) +
  transition_states(
    month_label,
    transition_length = 2,
    state_length = 1
  )

library(gganimate)
library(gifski)

anim <- animate(
  p,
  nframes = 200, fps = 10,
  width = 800, height = 600, units = "px",
  renderer = gifski_renderer()
)

anim_save("C:/Users/student/Desktop/bar_race.gif", animation = anim)

  4. ake a bar race using a dataset of your own interest. You may use the dataset that we use in class (https://covidtracking.com/data/download/all-states-history.csv) but you should make a different bar racev from ones in the slides.

library(tidyverse)
## Warning: package 'tidyverse' was built under R version 4.4.3
## Warning: package 'forcats' was built under R version 4.4.3
library(lubridate)
library(gganimate)
library(gifski)
library(readr)

df <- read_csv("https://covidtracking.com/data/download/all-states-history.csv")
## Warning: One or more parsing issues, call `problems()` on your data frame for details,
## e.g.:
##   dat <- vroom(...)
##   problems(dat)
top10_hosp <- df %>%
  mutate(date = ymd(date)) %>%
  filter(year(date) == 2021) %>%
  filter(!is.na(hospitalizedCurrently)) %>%
  select(date, state, hospitalizedCurrently) %>%
  group_by(date, state) %>%
  summarise(hosp = max(hospitalizedCurrently, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = hosp, n = 10, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  arrange(date, hosp) %>%
  mutate(
    rank = row_number(),
    date_label = format(date, "%b %d %Y")
  ) %>%
  ungroup()
p <- ggplot(top10_hosp,
            aes(x = hosp,
                y = reorder(state, rank),
                fill = state)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    x = "Current Covid-19 hospitalizations",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Top-10 states by current Covid-19 hospitalizations\n{closest_state}"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "none",
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold")
  ) +
  transition_states(
    date_label,
    transition_length = 2,
    state_length = 1
  )

library(gganimate)
library(gifski)

anim <- animate(
  p,
  nframes = 200, fps = 10,
  width = 800, height = 600, units = "px",
  renderer = gifski_renderer()
)

anim_save("C:/Users/student/Desktop/bar_race.gif", animation = anim)
